19:08.405 --> 19:16.734
And Jesus came to comfort Martha and Mary, and he said this in John 1125, I am the resurrection and the life.

19:17.756 --> 19:21.340
The one who believes in me will live even though they die.

19:21.860 --> 19:23.442
We still face permanent endings.

19:23.874 --> 19:27.138
but never without the hope of a brand new beginning of life eternal.

19:28.200 --> 19:32.705
And then Jesus said, and whoever lives by believing in me never really dies.

19:37.892 --> 19:44.341
So I was standing at my dad's grave, permanent ending.

19:47.725 --> 19:51.570
And I was still able to find and know and experience hope

19:53.794 --> 20:00.182
because I knew my dad, though he had died, was still alive.

20:01.764 --> 20:14.078
This Easter celebration is no little thing because it tells us as Jesus walked out of that tomb so we can experience life after our death and all we have to do is believe.

20:14.419 --> 20:17.462
One of the most beautiful memories I have was at my dad's funeral.

20:18.764 --> 20:20.466
He had polio and he was 17.

20:21.538 --> 20:28.669
And we put his crutches leaning up against his casket, knowing that he would never need them again.

20:30.151 --> 20:33.156
Because our permanent endings are God's brand new beginnings.

20:34.077 --> 20:38.444
And I have to, I just want to share this real life personal thing with you.

20:38.484 --> 20:46.517
If you've been at Northridge a long time, you've heard about my dad, hey, it's a good thing when a son can talk about their dad in a positive way.

20:48.740 --> 20:50.002
This is a picture of my dad.

20:52.002 --> 20:54.386
By the way, he was a pretend farmer.

20:54.646 --> 20:55.808
I'm just telling you right now.

20:57.250 --> 21:01.075
He was really a lawyer and a judge and a land developer.

21:01.096 --> 21:02.337
This was a joke right here.

21:02.377 --> 21:05.061
But I mean, he loved it for some reason.

21:05.182 --> 21:05.742
I don't get it.

21:06.283 --> 21:08.446
Get something faster, Dad, was my thought.

21:08.486 --> 21:09.929
But anyway, he loved it.

21:10.990 --> 21:14.616
But you know, he started in a broken and impoverished family.

21:16.719 --> 21:18.962
The word privilege never touched this guy's life.

21:20.258 --> 21:25.505
His dad was a raging alcoholic, dysfunctional, broken man who didn't invest in his family.

21:25.525 --> 21:32.194
He was crazy, and his mom, my dad's mom, of course, became this broken and dysfunctional woman.

21:34.257 --> 21:45.613
And my dad, when he was seven years old, in this family of agony, got TB and was put in a home by himself as a seven-year-old kid until he healed for a year.

21:45.633 --> 21:46.514
He was there.

21:47.778 --> 21:50.924
Then when he was 17, he got polio and lost the use of his legs.

21:53.088 --> 21:56.315
Took him a year to develop with crutches, the ability to walk a little bit.

21:58.759 --> 22:07.436
And yet this man who had no encouragement from anyone decided, I'm going to make something of my life and find happiness.

22:07.517 --> 22:10.322
And so he put himself through high school.

22:11.202 --> 22:21.153
He put himself through college, he put himself through grad school, and then he put himself through law school, started a very successful law firm, became a judge, a land developer, a very successful guy.

22:21.173 --> 22:33.386
